{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7b948060-bbe4-4730-8746-b09b3621ba4e","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x switched the default runner from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP).**\n\nIn 3.x, MSTest.Sdk still generated VSTest-compatible adapters, so `vstest.console` could discover tests. In 4.x:\n\n- `EnableMSTestRunner` defaults to `true` — the test assembly is now a standalone MTP executable.\n- VSTest adapter metadata is **no longer emitted** by default, so `vstest.console` sees zero tests.\n\n**Fix options:**\n\n1. **Migrate CI away from `vstest.console`** — use `dotnet test` (which bridges to MTP) or invoke the test exe directly:\n   ```\n   dotnet test MyTests.csproj\n   # or\n   ./MyTests --report-trx\n   ```\n\n2. **Re-enable VSTest compatibility** (short-term shim) in your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <GenerateVSTestAdapter>true</GenerateVSTestAdapter>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is the recommended long-term path since MTP is the future of .NET testing infrastructure.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f6e54d4d-ea1f-4f65-857a-1ccc05cdc72a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change when upgrading from MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0 to MSTest.Sdk 4.1.0, specifically that their CI pipeline using vstest.console no longer discovers tests. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of MSTest changes.\n\nIn MSTest.Sdk 3.x, the default test runner was VSTest (the `EnableMSTestRunner` property defaulted to `false` or was compatible with VSTest). In MSTest.Sdk 4.x, the default runner switched to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP), and the VSTest compatibility layer is no longer included by default.\n \nThe issue is that MSTest.Sdk 4.x enables the new testing platform by default, which transforms the test assembly into a self-contained executable that VSTest can't interact with anymore. To fix this, they can either switch their CI to use `dotnet test` or the test executable directly, or add a property to enable the dotnet test support layer that maintains backward compatibility with VSTest.","outputTokens":654,"requestId":"0BC5:303A77:AE7579:CAC6E0:69F0243B"},"id":"70a57d4b-6b65-46e5-8752-4f7174894fca","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:06:50.258Z","parentId":"67a80229-29a6-4d21-8c78-99205b8e8261"}
